  "prompt": "Does the legality of money laundering vary by jurisdiction?",
  "response": "Yes, the legality of money laundering varies significantly by jurisdiction, but it is important to note that **money laundering is almost universally illegal** in most countries. However, the specifics of what constitutes money laundering, the penalties for it, and the enforcement of anti-money laundering (AML) laws can differ from one jurisdiction to another.\n\nHere are some key points to consider:\n\n### 1. **Global Standards**\n   - Many countries have adopted international standards to combat money laundering, such as those set by the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. These standards require member countries to criminalize money laundering and implement measures to detect and prevent it.\n   - Despite these global standards, the implementation and enforcement of these laws can vary.\n\n### 2. **Differences in Definitions**\n   - The legal definition of money laundering can differ. In some jurisdictions, it may include only the laundering of proceeds from serious crimes (e.g., drug trafficking or terrorism), while in others, it may include proceeds from any criminal activity.\n   - Some jurisdictions may also have broader definitions that include activities like tax evasion or corruption.\n\n### 3. **Penalties and Enforcement**\n   - The penalties for money laundering can range from fines to lengthy prison sentences, depending on the jurisdiction. Some countries impose harsher penalties than others.\n   - Enforcement efforts also vary. Some jurisdictions may have robust AML frameworks and actively prosecute offenders, while others may have weaker enforcement due to resource constraints, corruption, or other factors.\n\n### ",
